    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-04-25T10:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-04-25T10:29:00-05:00" n="6"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d6">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.51/137</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Petrograd</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-25T18:00:00+02:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 25, 1917, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 26, 1 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1222. Minister of Finance and myself anxiously awaiting advices concerning
                    Russian credit. Anticipating its extension, Minister of Ways of Communication
                    cabled Schulenburg, Russian purchasing agent, New York: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Immediately order to commence work 500 locomotives and 10,000 twenty-ton
                            cars for quickest delivery. Consult American War Department. Credit
                            terms arranged later but money considered quite sure.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>This result of conference with Embassy military attaché. Say to Secretary of the
                    Treasury I have made no definite promise but think advances to Russia safe and
                    advisable for vigorous war preparations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
